# Job Scoring & Grading Rules
# Copy this file to grading_rules.md and fill in your own profile.

## Step 1: Language requirement (jd_language_req)

Scan the full JD and assign one of the following values:

en_required (English-only environment — prioritise these)
  → signals: English, English-speaking, no German required,
             office/working language is English, language: English

de_plus (German is a bonus — still acceptable)
  → signals: German is a plus, German preferred, German nice to have,
             Deutsch von Vorteil, Deutschkenntnisse von Vorteil

de_required (fluent German required — skip unless deliberately targeting)
  → signals: C1, C2, fluent German, verhandlungssicher Deutsch,
             fließend Deutsch, Kundenkontakt, auf Deutsch

unknown (no language requirement mentioned)

## Step 2: match_score (0–100)

Evaluate how well the job fits the candidate's technical background:
- Core skills: <YOUR_CORE_TECH_STACK e.g. Python, Node.js, FastAPI, Docker, CI/CD, LLM>
- Experience: <YOUR_EXPERIENCE e.g. 4+ years Backend Engineer with Tech Lead experience>
- Languages: <YOUR_LANGUAGES e.g. English fluent, German A2>
- Location bonus: <YOUR_TARGET_LOCATIONS e.g. Hamburg, Remote, Hybrid>

Score anchors — use these to calibrate your number:
- 85–100: Near-perfect fit — core stack explicitly required, seniority aligns, preferred language and location
- 70–84:  Strong match — most core skills required, 1–2 minor gaps, or adjacent role (e.g. MLOps/Data Engineer with heavy Python)
- 50–69:  Partial match — overlapping stack but notable gaps (e.g. different primary language, no AI focus, or German required)
- 30–49:  Weak match — different primary stack or domain, limited transferable skills
-  0–29:  Poor fit — unrelated domain or almost no skill overlap

## Step 3: visa_restriction

Scan the JD and assign one of the following values:

open (no restrictions, or actively welcoming international candidates)
  → signals: no restricting language, or: international team, diverse backgrounds,
             global team, relocation package, open to international candidates

eu_only (requires existing work authorisation — no sponsorship offered)
  → signals: EU citizens only, must have right to work in Germany,
             valid work permit required, eligible to work without sponsorship,
             no visa sponsorship, Arbeitserlaubnis erforderlich, EU-Bürger bevorzugt,
             Aufenthaltstitel, legally authorized to work

sponsored (company actively offers visa/relocation support)
  → signals: visa sponsorship provided, we sponsor work permits,
             support with visa, relocation support including visa,
             help with work authorization

unclear (no visa-related mention)

## Step 4: salary_range

Copy the salary information verbatim from the JD if present.
Examples: "€60,000–€80,000/year", "60k–80k EUR", "TVöD E13", "bis zu 90.000 € brutto".
Use an empty string "" if not mentioned.

## Step 5: contract_type

Assign one of the following values:

permanent (full-time permanent position)
  → signals: Festanstellung, unbefristete Stelle, permanent position,
             full-time employee, unbefristet

contract (fixed-term or temporary)
  → signals: befristet, temporary, fixed-term, limited contract, Werkvertrag

freelance (self-employed / contractor)
  → signals: freelance, Freiberufler, contractor, self-employed, consulting role

unknown (not mentioned)

## Cover Letter (English, 200–400 words, end on a complete sentence)

Para 1 (2–3 sentences): role applied for + core motivation
Para 2 (3–4 sentences): 1–2 relevant technical achievements with concrete results
Para 3 (1–2 sentences): company interest + polite close
Tone: formal but direct. Avoid clichés like "I am a passionate developer".
